ce: Integration=0.65, Agentic=0.3, Unit=0.05\n\nFor Behavior 1, I'm reconsidering whether Integration testing would suffice instead of Agentic. With Integration, I'd use a real LLM in a single call and verify the signature matches the expected interface. But looking at the definitions again — Integration involves multiple modules with local resources, while Agentic specifically accounts for real LLM non-determinism — these might actually be the same approach here since both would use a real LLM. The distinction matters more when testing behaviors that depend on iterative refinement or external variability.\n\nI'm also clarifying the relationship between System and Agentic tests. System covers real HTTP calls and external APIs generally, while Agentic is specifically for LLM or AI/ML model calls. A real LLM call via HTTP technically fits both categories, but Agentic is the more precise classification since it captures the non-deterministic nature of the model's output. The hierarchy seems to be Unit < Integration < System < Agentic < Workflow, where System handles general external dependencies and Agentic specifically addresses AI/ML model behavior.\n\nFor the behaviors: one real LLM call is Agentic, multiple sequential LLM calls become Workflow, mocked LLM tests stay at Integration, and end-to-end verification with real models is Workflow. Now I'm ready to assign confidence distributions to each behavior.\n\n**Behavior 1: Signature matching**\n\nThe core question is whether this tests the LLM's generation capability or just extraction logic. Since the behavior explicitly checks that \"the generated function signature matches the expected interface,\" it's fundamentally about what the model produces, not parsing. This pushes Agentic higher—around 0.85—since I need the actual LLM to verify correctness. System drops to 0.1 if focusing on the HTTP layer, Unit stays minimal at 0.07 since it's not purely about extraction, and Integration at 0.03 for mock scenarios. Workflow doesn't apply here since there's only one call.\n\n**Behavior 2: Passes tests**\n\nThis one requires iterative refinement—the model generates code, tests run, failures feed back in, and the model tries again. That's a Workflow pattern at 0.85 confidence. I could test a single generation attempt at Agentic level (0.1), or emphasize the HTTP mechanics at System (0.03), but the multi-turn feedback loop is the defining characteristic. Unit and Integration are negligible.\n\n**Behavior 3: Failure messages in prompt**\n\nTo verify this, I'd need to generate code with a real LLM, execute tests (which could be subprocess or mocked), then make a second LLM call that includes those failure messages. Integration fits best at 0.7 since I can mock the LLM while inspecting what actually gets sent in the second prompt. Agentic works at 0.2 if I'm testing that learning genuinely occurs across calls. Unit testing just the prompt-building logic gets 0.07. System and Workflow are unlikely here.\n\n**Behavior 4: Stops after 3 attempts**\n\nThis is about control flow—mocking the LLM and test runner, then verifying the loop terminates correctly. Integration at 0.8 handles that well. Unit testing just the counter logic gets 0.12. System testing with a real test runner might expose edge cases (0.05). Agentic and Workflow are minimal.\n\n**Behavior 5: Full loop produces working code**\n\nThe entire iterative cycle with multiple LLM calls and refinement steps points to Workflow at 0.85. A single LLM call with retries could work at Agentic (0.1), and emphasizing subprocess behavior pushes toward System (0.03). Unit and Integration are too narrow for this end-to-end behavior.\n\nI should also reconsider what \"plan_consistent\" really means—whether each test actually demands the level I've assigned, or if a lower level would suffice.\n\nFor Behavior 1, if I claim it requires Agentic, the test must genuinely need a real LLM. Mocking the LLM would let any signature pass if I mock the right output, so I'd miss real failures. That's why Agentic is necessary—only a real LLM call reveals whether the signature extraction actually works.\n\nFor Behavior 2, calling a real LLM with code that fails tests, then verifying the failure messages appear in the next prompt, requires either mocking both the LLM and test runner (Integration) or using real components. If I mock the LLM to return failing code and mock the test runner to report failures, I can verify the messages flow through. That's Integration-level and sufficient—I don't need a real LLM to test message inclusion.\n\nFor Behavior 3, the test needs multiple sequential LLM calls with feedback loops. A single call won't work because I need to verify the model actually improves after seeing failures. This demands Workflow level, where the LLM refines code based on test output across multiple iterations.\n\nBehavior 4 checks that the system stops after 3 failed attempts and collects all results. I can mock the LLM and test runner to control outcomes, then verify the exit condition and error aggregation. This stays at Integration level since I'm testing the control flow with mocked dependencies.\n\nBehavior 5 requires a real LLM and real test execution to confirm the full refinement loop actually produces working code on complex tasks. This is System level because I need genuine model behavior and test results, not mocked responses.\n\nNow for the behavior descriptions themselves. Behavior 1 tests that the LLM generates code with the correct function signature by calling the real model with specific parameter requirements, parsing the output with AST analysis, and validating the names, types, and return type match expectations. This is Agentic level since it's a single LLM call with straightforward output validation.\n\nBehavior 2 requires the full workflow: generate code, run it against tests, potentially refine based on failures, and repeat until passing. This is Workflow level because it involves multiple sequential steps where the LLM may need to iterate and improve its output based on test feedback.\n\nThe key insight is that mocking would let us artificially control whether refinement succeeds, masking whether the real model actually improves code quality when given test failures. The real failure mode—where all three attempts fail or refinement doesn't help—only surfaces with genuine LLM calls and authentic test results. A test case designed to fail initially (like a subtle off-by-one error) would verify the loop actually converges through real refinement.\n\nFor the second behavior, I need to verify that failure messages get threaded into subsequent prompts. This is a mechanical concern about prompt construction that mocking can effectively validate—I'd mock the LLM to produce failing code, capture the test output, then inspect the second call's prompt argument to confirm it includes those failure details. Unit tests could cover the prompt-building logic in isolation, but Integration testing with mocked LLM responses is the right level to ensure the full flow works.\n\nThe third behavior addresses what happens when refinement attempts exhaust. After three failed tries, the service should return a structured response indicating failure rather than continuing indefinitely.\n\nIntegration testing is appropriate here since we need to verify the loop's control flow—specifically that it terminates at exactly three attempts and packages results correctly. Mocking the LLM to consistently produce failing code and the test runner to report failures lets us exercise the retry logic without external dependencies. The test would run the full generation-test-refine cycle, then confirm the service exits after the third failure and returns an error object containing all attempts with their corresponding test results.\n\nFor the end-to-end workflow, a real LLM and test suite are necessary. This validates that the system can actually solve non-trivial problems through iterative refinement—cases where a single generation attempt isn't sufficient. The test selects a task with known complexity (like an algorithm with edge cases), runs the full loop with genuine feedback from test failures, and confirms the final implementation passes all tests. For signature matching, the real LLM is essential to verify the generated function has the correct parameters and return type, so Agentic dominates at 0.85. System testing could emphasize the HTTP interaction but Agentic already covers that. Unit and Integration are minimal since the core behavior is about generation, not extraction or mocking.\n\nFor the iterative refinement behavior, Workflow takes 0.85 because it's the only level that exercises multiple LLM calls with feedback loops. A single Agentic call can't verify the full iteration cycle works end-to-end. System, Unit, and Integration contribute minimally—they either focus on HTTP mechanics or can't capture the convergence behavior that requires real feedback.\n\nWhen testing that failure messages get incorporated into prompts, Integration is strongest at 0.70 since I can mock the LLM and inspect what gets passed to it. Agentic testing would verify learning happens but isn't as direct. Unit testing could check prompt-building logic in isolation, though that's not the main concern.\n\nFor the three-attempt limit, Integration leads at 0.80 because it combines mock LLM behavior, test runner control, and verifiable control flow. Unit testing covers just the counter logic at 0.12. System and Agentic contribute less since the behavior is about orchestration, not real LLM calls or HTTP specifics.\n\nFinally, validating that the full loop produces working code requires Workflow at 0.85—only real LLM calls across multiple iterations can demonstrate actual convergence. Agentic testing with a single call and retries doesn't capture the complete feedback cycle. Integration mocks would miss whether the system truly converges to functional code.","signature":""